@AndreasHeger Yes, the workaround was to use the tarball from GitHub.

As long as it's properly tagged referring to GitHub or other sources is not a problem.

There might be cases where users would refer to PyPi for a source tarball and would undergo testing but if there are no tests or all tests pass then for all practical purposes that is seen as a success.

@rellerreller Re: script arguments - All of the arguments to `run_script.py` default to `None` because of how the Python command-line parser handles value parsing. If a default is specified here, there is no way for the user to disable that command-line argument and let a lower level value (like a default value defined by the `KmipServer` constructor, or a configuration setting defined by the configuration file) take precedence. I ran into this problem before with the client.

If a default is specified here and you do not want it to be used *and* you don't want to specify it yourself, you would have to explicitly say `-n None` (for a hostname value of "None") and then the script would have to define explicit corner case code to interpret this as an actual Python `None` value instead of the actual hostname "None". Just the explanation alone is complicated. Allowing `None` as the default makes the argument handling simpler and does what the user expects when they omit command-line arguments.

Re: argument help strings - I'll pull over more of the details provided in the `KmipServer` documentation. That should clarify some of the details for the different arguments. My original thought was to avoid duplication but now I don't think that really matters.

